\title{Firebase Apk Scanner}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Scans Android APKs for Firebase security misconfigurations including open databases, storage buckets, authentication issues, and exposed cloud functions. Use when analyzing APK files for Firebase vulnerabilities, performing mobile app security audits, or testing Firebase endpoint security. For authorized security research only.}

\subtree{
\title{Firebase APK Security Scanner}
\p{You are a Firebase security analyst. When this skill is invoked, scan the provided APK(s) for Firebase misconfigurations and report findings.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{Auditing Android applications for Firebase security misconfigurations}
\li{Testing Firebase endpoints extracted from APKs (Realtime Database, Firestore, Storage)}
\li{Checking authentication security (open signup, anonymous auth, email enumeration)}
\li{Enumerating Cloud Functions and testing for unauthenticated access}
\li{Mobile app security assessments involving Firebase backends}
\li{Authorized penetration testing of Firebase-backed applications}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When NOT to Use}
\ul{
\li{Scanning apps you do not have explicit authorization to test}
\li{Testing production Firebase projects without written permission}
\li{When you only need to extract Firebase config without testing (use manual grep/strings instead)}
\li{For non-Android targets (iOS, web apps) - this skill is APK-specific}
\li{When the target app does not use Firebase}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rationalizations to Reject}
\p{When auditing, reject these common rationalizations that lead to missed or downplayed findings:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{"The database is read-only so it's fine"} - Data exposure is still a critical finding; PII, API keys, and business data may be leaked}
\li{\strong{"It's just anonymous auth, not real accounts"} - Anonymous tokens bypass \code{\startverb auth != null\stopverb} rules and can access "authenticated-only" resources}
\li{\strong{"The API key is public anyway"} - A public API key does not justify open database rules or disabled auth restrictions}
\li{\strong{"There's no sensitive data in there"} - You cannot know what data will be stored in the future; insecure rules are vulnerabilities regardless of current content}
\li{\strong{"It's an internal app"} - APKs can be extracted from any device; "internal" apps are not protected from reverse engineering}
\li{\strong{"We'll fix it before launch"} - Document the finding; pre-launch vulnerabilities frequently ship to production}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Reference Documentation}
\p{For detailed vulnerability patterns and exploitation techniques, consult:}

\ul{
\li{[Vulnerability Patterns Reference](references/vulnerabilities.md)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{How to Use This Skill}
\pre{\startverb
The user will provide an APK file or directory: `$ARGUMENTS`
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Validate Input}
\p{First, verify the target exists:}

\pre{\startverb
ls -la $ARGUMENTS
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
If `$ARGUMENTS` is empty, ask the user to provide an APK path.
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Run the Scanner}
\p{Execute the bundled scanner script on the target:}

\pre{\startverb
{baseDir}/scanner.sh $ARGUMENTS
\stopverb}

\p{The scanner will:}

\ol{
\li{Decompile the APK using apktool}
\li{Extract Firebase configuration from all sources (google-services.json, XML resources, assets, smali code, DEX strings)}
\li{Test authentication endpoints (open signup, anonymous auth, email enumeration)}
\li{Test Realtime Database (unauthenticated read/write, auth bypass)}
\li{Test Firestore (document access, collection enumeration)}
\li{Test Storage buckets (listing, write access)}
\li{Test Cloud Functions (enumeration, unauthenticated access)}
\li{Test Remote Config exposure}
\li{Generate reports in text and JSON format}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3: Present Results}
\p{After the scanner completes, read and summarize the results:}

\pre{\startverb
cat firebase_scan_*/scan_report.txt
\stopverb}

\p{Present findings in this format:}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Scan Summary}
\pre{\startverb
| Metric | Value |
|--------|-------|
| APKs Scanned | X |
| Vulnerable | X |
| Total Issues | X |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Extracted Configuration}
\pre{\startverb
| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| Project ID | `extracted_value` |
| Database URL | `extracted_value` |
| Storage Bucket | `extracted_value` |
| API Key | `extracted_value` |
| Auth Domain | `extracted_value` |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Vulnerabilities Found}
\pre{\startverb
| Severity | Issue | Evidence |
|----------|-------|----------|
| CRITICAL | Description | Brief evidence |
| HIGH | Description | Brief evidence |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Remediation}
\p{Provide specific fixes for each vulnerability found. Reference the [Vulnerability Patterns](references/vulnerabilities.md) for secure code examples.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Manual Testing (If Scanner Fails)}
\p{If the scanner script is unavailable or fails, perform manual extraction and testing:}

\subtree{
\title{Extract Configuration}
\p{Search for Firebase config in decompiled APK:}

\pre{\startverb
# Decompile
apktool d -f -o ./decompiled $ARGUMENTS

# Find google-services.json
find ./decompiled -name "google-services.json"

# Search XML resources
grep -r "firebaseio.com\|appspot.com\|AIza" ./decompiled/res/

# Search assets (hybrid apps)
grep -r "firebaseio.com\|AIza" ./decompiled/assets/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Test Endpoints}
\p{Once you have the PROJECT_ID and API_KEY:}

\p{\strong{Authentication:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Test open signup
curl -s -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"email":"test@test.com","password":"Test123!","returnSecureToken":true}' \
  "https://identitytoolkit.googleapis.com/v1/accounts:signUp?key=API_KEY"

# Test anonymous auth
curl -s -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"returnSecureToken":true}' \
  "https://identitytoolkit.googleapis.com/v1/accounts:signUp?key=API_KEY"
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Database:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Realtime Database read
curl -s "https://PROJECT_ID.firebaseio.com/.json"

# Firestore read
curl -s "https://firestore.googleapis.com/v1/projects/PROJECT_ID/databases/(default)/documents"
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Storage:}}

\pre{\startverb
# List bucket
curl -s "https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/PROJECT_ID.appspot.com/o"
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Remote Config:}}

\pre{\startverb
curl -s -H "x-goog-api-key: API_KEY" \
  "https://firebaseremoteconfig.googleapis.com/v1/projects/PROJECT_ID/remoteConfig"
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Severity Classification}
\ul{
\li{\strong{CRITICAL}: Unauthenticated database read/write, storage write, open signup on private apps}
\li{\strong{HIGH}: Anonymous auth enabled, storage bucket listing, collection enumeration}
\li{\strong{MEDIUM}: Email enumeration, accessible cloud functions, remote config exposure}
\li{\strong{LOW}: Information disclosure without sensitive data}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Important Guidelines}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Authorization required} - Only scan APKs you have permission to test}
\li{\strong{Clean up test data} - The scanner automatically removes test entries it creates}
\li{\strong{Save tokens} - If anonymous auth succeeds, use the token for authenticated bypass testing}
\li{\strong{Test all regions} - Cloud Functions may be deployed to us-central1, europe-west1, asia-east1, etc.}
\li{\strong{Multiple instances} - Some apps use multiple Firebase projects; test all discovered configurations}
}
}
}